-Exploring Inference-Time Defenses and Output Perturbation The CDML operates primarily at the feature embedding level. You could enlarge your defense mechanism by adding safeguards at the output level using inference-time output perturbation. Since adversaries often exploit the confidence values revealed alongside predictions to execute label-only or confidence-based attacks, you could implement prediction purification or inject calibrated adversarial noise into the final softmax likelihood arrays. This complements the CDML by ensuring that even if an attacker guesses the modulating code, the final output cannot be easily exploited.

-Synergizing CDML with Wavelet-Guided Generative Replay Your paper correctly highlights that storing raw biometric data for replay violates privacy policies and increases storage costs. However, to further boost accuracy in complex dataset-incremental scenarios without violating the non-storage constraint, you could explore Wavelet-guided Replay (R-Tuning). Since gait data is essentially a spatio-temporal signal, you can synthesize proxy samples using Redundant Wavelet Transform (RWT) to capture low-frequency trends and high-frequency variations from past data distributions. By passing these synthetic, frequency-aware samples through the CDML, you can enrich the diversity of the training data and prevent catastrophic forgetting without ever saving real user data


