-Integrating Machine Unlearning for the "Right to be Forgotten". Expanding the CDML architecture to support Machine Unlearning (MU) would allow the system to selectively erase the influence of specific individuals without requiring a complete retraining of the model from scratch,. You can implement mechanisms like Privacy-Guided Memory Sculpting to intelligently target and remove sensitive features from the model's parameters while preserving essential knowledge,. To evaluate the success of this unlearning, you should subject the unlearned model to Forensic Unlearning Membership Attacks (FUMA) to verify that the process leaves no detectable gradient artifacts that an adversary could exploit

-Securing Latent Representations with Geometric Regularization. If your system is eventually extended to use rehearsal buffers for advanced tasks, the uneven availability of past and present data can cause the model to overfit the memory buffer and entangle the latent representations of different individuals. You can improve the robustness of the latent space by applying regularizers like the Continual Spectral Regularizer (CaSpeR) or Lipschitz-Driven Experience Replay (LiDER), which enforce geometric constraints and ensure well-separated, robust latent embeddings

